  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Yeongga Yeonkwae Collection
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: 'Literature is a minor craft. Poetry and rhapsody are even more peripheral among the literary arts. Yet in cultivating nature and feeling, in spreading moral transformation and stirring the present age while transmitting beauty through endless generations, poetry and rhapsody play an essential role. Without the talent of heroes and sages, who could aspire to such heights? Though the talent of heroes exists in every age, rare indeed are those families where fathers and sons, grandfathers and grandsons, carry forward the legacy—preserving its brilliance and walking in its footsteps—thereby unfurling the accumulated wisdom of the ages and adorning the splendor of their nation. How many such exemplars grace history? In our Eastern land, we have the venerable scholars like Mokun, Seolgok, and Tongjung—masters whose fathers and sons alike left collections worthy of enumeration. Their achievement is truly remarkable. The house of Yeongga Kwon stands among these select few. How splendid this is! Not merely in letters alone, but through generations the brushmark of excellence flows unbroken. From Jijae through Sohandang, they have successively achieved supreme distinction—each a branch of laurel in the groves of art, each a jade fragment from the mountains of heaven, shining in the gardens of refinement and illuminating the halls of court. Their lifelong service to the state and their magnificent achievements rival those of Xiao and Zhang of Tang, Wang and Lü of Song. Truly glorious! Seokkangbu, the son of Sohandang, has worthily inherited this legacy. Before reaching manhood, he ascended through the highest examinations, from the Academy of Letters to the Silver Tower, where he now serves as Right Censor-General. The legacy of the Kwon family''s devotion to letters remains vibrant, showing no signs of waning. Seokkangbu has gathered and compiled the surviving writings of his grandfather and father into several volumes. The eminent Seo, Vice-Premier of Dalseong, inscribed upon it the title "Yeongga Yeonkwae Collection." Upon obtaining this work, I read it with care. The poetry of these two masters follows in form and tone the foundations laid by Yangchon, yet three generations of their composition have created their own distinct school. Their work is refined without descending into vulgarity, abundant without excess of embellishment. Some pieces possess classical dignity, others embody serene simplicity—between the two masters there is no distinction of superior or inferior. Zhuangzi once declared: "The father cannot transmit it to the son, nor can the son receive it from the father." Yet between these two, something appears to have been transmitted, something seems to have been received—something that transcends mere deliberation and craft. This springs from their natural endowment''s height and their learning''s profound attainment, each having reached the uttermost perfection of their art. In their conception and expression, there is a subtle, hidden accord, as if something were passed down and received—yet this remains something few in the world could comprehend. Thus, truly, these two exemplify the heroic talent we speak of. In this age when sagacious rule illuminates the throne and the culture of letters flourishes greatly, the surviving manuscripts of our predecessors often reach the imperial presence. This collection too shall surely endure alongside the works of Shin Mun-chung of Golyeong, Choe Mun-jeong of Yeongseong, Kang Mun-nyang of Jinsan, and Yi Mun-gan of Yangseong—transmitted and preserved through the ages without doubt. Even a thousand years hence, who would dare diminish it as mere minor craft?'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Mokun (牧隱), Seolgok (雪谷), and Tongjung (通亭) were celebrated Korean scholar-officials whose families maintained literary excellence across generations.
  - key: ''
    value: Jijae (止齋) and Sohandang (所閑堂) refer to Kwon Je and Kwon Nam respectively, distinguished members of the Yeongga Kwon family.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Xiao and Zhang of Tang, and Wang and Lü of Song, compares the Kwon family's political and literary achievements to the greatest statesmen of Chinese history.
  - key: ''
    value: The quotation from Zhuangzi refers to the transmission of profound wisdom that cannot be reduced to mere technique or conscious method.
